EDADSL LANGUAGE DESCRIPTION



assumed standard units:
lengh    in mm
all other units in simple SI units unless explicitly specified.

%N is new line
# initiates a comment untill a newline or %N
#{ opens a multiline comment and }# closes it

Variables:
assignment via
$<varname> <fitting assignment operator> <value>
$<varname> <fitting assignment operator> <value>; M = <Mutable?>

Assignment operators:
B=     bool
V=     scalar
S=     set
W=     string
L=     list

P=     part
C=     connection
T=     pin
N=     net

Variables are referenced by $<varname> and are by default mutable, but can be made to be immutable if M = False is passed.
example:
	$var1 V= 45
	$var2 V= 3 * $var1 + 7
	$var1 V= $var1 - $var2
	$var3 W= "protected var"; M = False



BASIC DATA TYPES:

bool:        True or False
scalar:      Single number
set:         Collection of certain objects
string:      Text
list:        Ordered list of objects

part:        Component in a circuit
connection:  Connection between parts
pin:         Connection-point of a part
net:         Collection of connections

bool:
creation via True or False

scalar:
creation via: a number ( integer or decimal ), <decimal part>e<exponent> or <value><decimal prefixe>
decimal prefixes:

q    1e-30  quecto
r    1e-27  ronto
y    1e-24  yocto
z    1e-21  zepto
a    1e-18  atto
f    1e-15  femto
p    1e-12  pico
n    1e-9   nano
u    1e-6   micro
m    1e-3   mili
c    1e-2   centi
d    1e-1   deci
     1e0
k    1e+3   kilo
M    1e+6   mega
G    1e+9   giga
T    1e+12  terra
P    1e+15  peta
E    1e+18  exa
Z    1e+21  zetta
Y    1e+24  yotta
R    1e+27  ronna
Q    1e+30  quetta

examples:
	0     # = 0
	700   # = 700
	-35   # = -35
	+80   # = 80
	6.94  # = 6.94
	2e-6  # = 0.000002
	-5e9  # = -5000000000
	100n  # = 0.0000001
	6.2k  # = 6200
	4Q    # = 4000000000000000000000000000000

set:
creation via: {  <object 1>, ... , <object n>  }
NOTE:
a set may only contain the following object types: part, connection, pin, net
all other objects will be silently dropped.
example:
	$set S= { Q1, Q2, R5, Gnd, C7[1] }

string:
created via: "<text>" or '<text>'
example:
	"This is just some text."


list:
creation via: [ <object 1>, ... , <object n> ]
indexing via <list>[<index>] ( <object 1> has the index 0, <object n> has the index n - 1 )
additional list routines:
	[<start>:<increment>:<end>]
	[<start>:<end>] is equal to [<start>:1:<end>]
	[<start>|<end>|<number of elements>]

example:
	$list L= [ "Hi!", "This is a demo for", "LISTS!" ]
	print( $list[2] ) # console output: LISTS!
	[0|2|5] # is [0, 0.5, 1, 1.5, 2 ]

part:
creation via: part <reference>: <model>(<args of model>); des = <description>; fp = <footprint>
example:
	part "R3": R( R = 220, P = 0.25, type = "carbon" ); des = "220Ω quarter watt carbon resistor used for current limiting." ; fp = "Resistor_THT:R_Axial_DIN0309_L9.0mm_D3.2mm_P12.70mm_Horizontal"

connection:
Binary connections objects can be created via: ( <pin 1> | <pin 2> )
a set of pins can be passed as the second argument which will result in the return of a set of connections.
example:
	( R2[1] | J4[7] )

pin:
pin references are created via: <part ref>[<pin ref>]
example:
	Q3[c]

net:
creation via: net <net name>
example:
	net "Gnd"
	connect Gnd Q3[e] R1[2]
	print(Gnd) # console output: Net: "Gnd"; connections: Q3[e], R1[2]; tags: None



ELECTRICAL COMMANDS:

part <reference>: <model>(<args of model>); des = "description"; fp = <footprint>
Creates a component referenced via <reference> with a specified model
example:
	part "R3": R( R = 220, P = 0.25, type = "carbon" ); des = "220Ω quarter watt carbon resistor used for current limiting." ; fp = "Resistor_THT:R_Axial_DIN0309_L9.0mm_D3.2mm_P12.70mm_Horizontal"

NOTE: The footprint name should match the intended footprint in the kicad library if it is used.

part can also take a list of references.
example:
	part ["R3", "R6", "R32" ]: R( R = 220, P = 0.25, type = "carbon" ); des = "220Ω quarter watt carbon resistor used for current limiting."; fp = Resistor_THT:R_Axial_DIN0309_L9.0mm_D3.2mm_P12.70mm_Horizontal

connect <pin 1 / net reference> <pin 2> ... <pin n>
joins all listed pins together. Note that only one net can be referenced as the 1st object.
example:
	connect Gnd Q2[s] C6[-] R3[2]

net <net name> <tag 1> ... <tag n>
creates a net with the specified name and optinal tags
Example:
	net "Gnd"
	net "hvbus" "hv" "high_i" "noisy"

tag <net name> <tag1>, ..., <tag n>
tags a net with specified tags
example:
	tag Vin "sensitive"
	tag hvVcc "high_voltage", "danger", "isolate_from_lv"

untag <net name> <tag1>, ..., <tag n>
removes all specified tags from a net
example:
	tag hvVcc "high_voltage", "danger", "isolate_from_lv", "safe"
	untag hvVcc "safe"



PHYSICAL CONSTRAINTS:

priorities:
-d (or blank):  default
-nth:           nice to have
-imp:           important
-vimp:          very important
-oeo:           only explicit overrides
-ne:            no exceptions
-nonneg:        non negotiable
-eo:            explicit override of a previous rule

proirity chain: -d < -nth < -imp < -vimp < -oeo < -eo < -ne = -nonneg


phy.prox <set a> <set b> min = <min distance between edges of a and b> max = <max distance anything in a can be away from anything in b> <priority>

phy.prox <set> minim <priority>
tries to minimize the distance between all objects in <set>
example:
	phy.prox $hvsys $lvsys min=15 -ne
	phy.prox $noisy_loop minim -vimp

phy.layer <set> <layer> <priority>
<side> is an integer. layer 0 is the top while the bottom layer is the nth layer.
example:
	phy.side *p 0 -oeo

phy.creep <set a> <set b> d = <minimum creepage distance> <priority>
example:
	phy.creep $hvsys $lvsys d = 30 -nonneg

NOTE: phy.prox is raw euclidean distance, phy.creep is surface distance (affected by slots, the board, vias, traces, ect) and conductive material contributes 0 distance. 

phy.board N = <number of board layers> T = <list containing the thicknesses between layers in mm, l = n - 1> W = <list containing the thicknesses of layers in oz/ft², l = n> M = [<dielectric material>, <conductive material>, <surface-plating material>]
specifies board characteristics and can only be run once [top, ..., bottom]
running phy.board default is equivalent to phy.board N = 2 T = [ 1.6 ] W = [ 1, 1 ] M = ["FR4", "copper", "HASL"]
example:
	phy.board N = 2 T = [ 1.6 ] W = [ 2, 2 ] M = ["FR4", "copper", "ENIG" ]

phy.shrinknet <net> <priority>
tries to shrink <net> as much as possible.
example:
	net "Vsw"
	phy.shrinknet Vsw -Vimp

phy.mkplane <layer> <net>
creates a plane on <layer> which is connected to <net>
example:
	net "Gnd"
	phy.mkplane 1 Gnd

phy.viafill <Pad> v = <via hole diameter> d = <distance between centers of adjacent vias>
fills the referenced Pad with vias. Used for cooling for example DPak and D2Pak components.
example:
	part "Q1": MOSFET( type = "IRFS4115" ); des = "99A Id, 150V Vds, 10.3mOhm Rds, N-Channel HEXFET Power MOSFET, D2PAK"; fp = "Package_TO_SOT_SMD:TO-263-2"
	net "Gnd"
	connect Gnd Q1[d] # the drain is the large pad. I know that this example is electrically stupid, but it gets the point across.
	phy.mkplane 1 Gnd
	phy.viafill Q1[d] v = 0.25 d = 0.5

phy.connectioncurrent <connection / set containing connections> <rms current the connection must be able to carry> <priority>
sets the minimum rms current a connection must be able to carry
example:
	phy.connectioncurrent ( J1[2] | F1[1] ) 30 -oeo

phy.align <list of parts> axis = <x or y> d = <spacing between the edges> <priority>
aligns all given parts in the given order along the specified axis with the given edge-to-edge spacing.
example:
	part [ "Q1", "Q2" ]: mosfet( type = "C2M0025120D" ); des = "90A Id, 1200V Vds, 25mOhm, N-Channel SiC MOSFET, TO-247"; fp = "Package_TO_SOT_THT:TO-247-3_Horizontal_TabUp"
	phy.align [ Q1, Q2 ] axis = x d = 5 -vimp

phy.connmatch <property> <set of connections> <priority>
tries to minimize the by ||(<set of connections>) scaled variance of <property>
allowed properties:
len    lengh
res    resistance
ind    inducttance
cap    capacitance
imp    impedance
t      signal propagation time
example:
	phy.connmatch t $CPU_to_RAM_lines -vimp



FLOW CONTROLL:

if <boolean var>::{<condition dependent code>}
example:
	$c B= ||( $lvsys n $hvsys ) != 0
	if $c::{print("ISOLATION VIOLATION!")}

gotomarker <goto marker name>
creates a goto marker with a specefied name

gotojump <goto marker name>
jumps to a goto marker with a specified name
gotomarkers can jump out of functions and loops and nesting is allowed.
example:
	gotojump m1
	print( "This text will never be printed." )
	gotomarker m1

for <var> E <list>::{<code dependant on var>}
example:
	for $P E list(*t)::{ print( $P ) }

halt
halts the program and exports the logfile as well as all other created files. must be present at the end
example:
	halt

writetolog <string>
appends a string to the log file.
example:
	writetolog "test."

mkpcb
creates a pbc file based on the circuit and constraints specified above the mkpcb function.
example:
	mkpcb

mkschematic
creates a schematic file based on the circuit specified the mkschematic function.
example:
	mkschematic

echo <var>
prints <var> to the console
example:
	$s T= "error." %N echo $s



