	$a V= 3
	$b V= 5
	print( str( "The sum of ", $a, " and ", $b, " is ", $a + $b, "." ) )  # console output: The sum of 3 and 5 is 8.


<quantifier>@<netname>
is the set of everything physical specefied by <quantifier> connected to <netname>
quantifiers:
P              parts
C              connections
T              pins
I              connections and pins
H              holes
E (or nothing) everything
example:
	$input S= I@Vin

<quantifier>@^<tag>
is expanded to
<quantifier>@<1st net with tag> u ... u <quantifier>@<nth net with tag>
example:
	tag Vin "sensitive"
	tag Vfb "sensitive"
	I@^sensitive


custom function creation:
function creation is accomplished via: function <name>(<arguments>)::{<code of the function>}
to make the function return a value the variable $retval must be set
function work on the global scope
example:
	function log3( $x )::{ $retval V= ln( $x ) / ln( 3 ) }
	print( log3( 9 ) ) # console output: 2



RESOLVING A GIVEN SET OF PHYSICAL CONSTRAINTS:

if all constraints can be simply satisfied without conflicts the solution is complete.

if there is a conflict between constraints with different priorities:
	the rule with the higher priority is satisfied while the one with the lower priority is optimized as much as possible without impairing the higher rule
	a warning is printed to the console

if there is a conflict between constraints with the same priority:
	the behavior depends on the priority:
		-d, -nth, -imp, -vimp:
			an error message is printed to the console
			the program continues
		-oeo, -eo, -ne, nonneg:
			an error message is printed to the console
			the program does not continue










